Petal Pink Font Rose family Flower Arranging Floristry Cut flowers Garden roses Floral design Rose Book of Proverbs
Date: 2021-02-01 00:45:31
Caption: You might have read our recent post about the excessive use of damaging pesticides in imported cut flowers, but of almost equal concern is fungicide usage. You see, Ecuador, where many of the roses sold in the US are grown, has high amounts of rainfall and the greenhouses where these flowers are grown are notorious for holding in humidity and creating fungus issues like Botrytis. Botrytis can create spots on a rose, and often won't appear on a rose until after it's left the farm. To prevent these spots from showing up on roses once they hit the retail market and dissuading customers from buying them, foreign growers have developed a worrisome and toxic method of dipping the entire rose into a vat of fungicide, first dunking the bloom, and then the stem. The workers in charge of this job wear respirator masks to avoid inhaling the products, which are then packaged directly into flower sleeves and shipped to the US (no, they are not rinsed off afterward). Of the 37 products that are used as rose dip treatments, 17 of them have been identified by the Pesticide Action Network to be problematic as groundwater pollutants or harmful to humans, toxic to life and the environment. Unfortunately, Valentine's Day, the biggest flower holiday in the US, is also a time when domestic roses are, by and large, dormant in their fields. This means the VAST majority of cut roses purchased during February have been dipped in a toxic blend of fungicides and pesticides. Not exactly the way I'd want to say "I love you!" #flowers #colorado #coloradoflorist #farmerflorist #coloradofarmer #localflowers #pesticides #fungicides #toxicflowers #valentinesdayflowers #valentinesday #denver #denverflorist #roses #importedroses #buyamericangrown #americangrown #supportlocalflowers #supportamericanfarms #buyamericangrown #coloradogrown #freshcutcolorado #coloradoflowers

Caption: A critically endangered fungus - Tea-tree Fingers. This colony was only recently discovered by colleagues and is bigger than all the other previously known fruiting bodies combined. And it's the only colony within a National Park. The whacky thing is it feeds on another couple of specific species of fungi, so to conserve this fungus, we must conserve its hosts first. The other colonies are threatened by sand mining activity. #teatreefingers #rememberthewild #wildvictoria #VicOurNature #fungimap #endangered #SaveWesternportWoodlands

Caption: The brightly-coloured waxcaps are often thought of as the orchids of the fungi kingdom because they are so vibrant and showy, and also quite particular. They will only grow on undisturbed, nutrient-poor grasslands like ancient pasture and other land that has never been ploughed or fertilised. As a result, many species are rare and hard to find but some grow much closer to home â€“ literally. Waxcaps can appear in garden lawns, grassy churchyards and even the occasional cricket pitch as long as the conditions are right. Wherever you find them, their presence means youâ€™re in a very special place. Caption: Did you know that improper storage of grains and nuts could result in the production of a potent toxin? Aflatoxin B2 is mainly produced by the fungi Aspergillus flavus. Aflatoxin-producing molds are commonly detected in inadequately stored agricultural produce, including maize, rice, cassava, cottonseed, millet, sorghum, sesame seeds, sweetcorn, chili peppers, tree nuts, sunflower seeds, spices, and wheat. Aflatoxin B2, while not as toxic as Aflatoxin B1, can affect children, leading to delays in development and stunted growth. Prolonged exposure has also been linked to liver cancer and liver impairment. #sigmaaldrich #chemistry #chemicals #moleculeoftheday #science #laboratory #supelco #32755 #fungi #fungifacts #naturalproducts

Happiness
Date: 2021-01-04 13:01:19
Caption: We must not continue down this path of indiscriminate war on microbes. ğŸ”¬ The soil microbes, and the beneficial microbes of our body, are the foundation of all life. In our misunderstanding and fear of specific microbes, we have launched an all out war on Nature. Bacteria, fungi, and viruses are critical to life on Earth. Antibiotics, pesticides and fungicides, sanitizers, etc are being used so injudiciously, that the very fabric of human and planetary health is at stake. We must learn the patience to discover the difference between friend and foe. As with all things in Nature, diversity is the key. Without diversity, the system collapses. The invisible microbes do not have a voice of their own - at least not in the traditional sense. But if we continue to ignore them, the microbial ecosystem will become so imbalanced that we will be forced to pay attention to their power. There is no life in a fully sterilized world. We must learn to live alongside these microbes, and acknowledge the significant role they play in the health of our planet. #microbes #invisible #tiny #microscopic #soilorganisms #organism #life #earth #motherearth #ecosystem #circleoflife #systemsthinking #systems #fungicides #pesticides

Date: 2022-08-02 05:09:43
Caption: Hexagonia tenuis fungi is plentiful in the regenerating native forests at the base of the escarpment. These areas were originally cleared for farmland and mining. The returning forests are only approximately 50 years into the process of establishing themselves again and I'm always in awe of their regenerative power. It's hard not to amorphosize natural phenomena with the constraints our language puts upon us. Fungi networks are described like the internet, beehives are described like officeworkers, but we know this is a crude way to narrate the complexity, abstraction, mystery and full expression of nature. So I tread tentatively knowing these words that follow are inept, but to experience a regenerating forest is to be part of a continual homecoming. With each species of native flora and fauna that returns I personally am exalted but there is no fanfare, fireworks or roll call within the forest itself. Instead a palatable gathering of strength and an emerging tranquillity spreads as each species reestablishes itself within the dynamics of the forest family. Many of the photos in this gallery are from this regenerating forest and it is a joy to share the homecoming of species like this fungi with you. #mycology #mycologysociety #fungus #mycologyphotography #fungilover #fungiphotography #fungifanatic #fantasticfungi #fungiofinstagram #fungiownunder #fungihunter #fungiaustralia #fungifreaks #fungihunting #fungiidentification #fungikingdom #fungilove #fungiphotography #fungioftheday #mushroom #mushrooms #mushlove #mushroomphotography #mushroomsofinstagram #australianfungi #fungi #forestbathing #forestfinds #naturesbeauty #forestlovers #biodiversity

Caption: Fomitopsis betulina EN This species is a saprotroph or parasite specific to Betula spp. It can be found on logs, dead trees, but sometimes in live trees too, although it possibly only infects already decaying, trees. Like other brown rot fungi it degrades the carbohydrate fraction of lignocellulose but, in contrast to white rot fungi, leaves lignin in the form of cubical brown fragments. Wood Fungus Trunk Polyporales Mushroom Forest Medicinal mushroom Inonotus Old-growth forest Jungle
Date: 2022-08-02 05:09:43
Caption: Hexagonia tenuis fungi is plentiful in the regenerating native forests at the base of the escarpment. These areas were originally cleared for farmland and mining. The returning forests are only approximately 50 years into the process of establishing themselves again and I'm always in awe of their regenerative power. It's hard not to amorphosize natural phenomena with the constraints our language puts upon us. Fungi networks are described like the internet, beehives are described like officeworkers, but we know this is a crude way to narrate the complexity, abstraction, mystery and full expression of nature. So I tread tentatively knowing these words that follow are inept, but to experience a regenerating forest is to be part of a continual homecoming. With each species of native flora and fauna that returns I personally am exalted but there is no fanfare, fireworks or roll call within the forest itself. Instead a palatable gathering of strength and an emerging tranquillity spreads as each species reestablishes itself within the dynamics of the forest family. Many of the photos in this gallery are from this regenerating forest and it is a joy to share the homecoming of species like this fungi with you. #mycology #mycologysociety #fungus #mycologyphotography #fungilover #fungiphotography #fungifanatic #fantasticfungi #fungiofinstagram #fungiownunder #fungihunter #fungiaustralia #fungifreaks #fungihunting #fungiidentification #fungikingdom #fungilove #fungiphotography #fungioftheday #mushroom #mushrooms #mushlove #mushroomphotography #mushroomsofinstagram #australianfungi #fungi #forestbathing #forestfinds #naturesbeauty #forestlovers #biodiversity

Caption: "Magic Mushroom Cultivationâ€ by Steven Pollock M.D. (1977) is one of the legendary texts in the cultivation of "magic mushrooms". Many popular books were published in the US during the 70â€™s about the cultivation of Psilocybe spp., but this one stands out as one of the better known, particularly because in time Pollock was (incorrectly) associated with the cubensis strain "P envy". Pollock is also well known for finding and cultivating P. tampanensis, aka "Philosophers Stones". Psilocybe cubensis is one of the most cultivated mushrooms, and as a consequence of extensive collection, cultivation, breeding, and marketing ploys by various spore print sellers numerous â€œstrainsâ€ now exist. Unfortunately, much of the history of many of the older strains has been lost, or exist within obfuscated narratives from a variety of websites, with the person/s responsible having disappeared into history. Cailleux and Heim were the first to grow cultures of P. cubensis (as Stropharia cubensis), publishing their methods in 1957. Caption: Of more than a hundred compounds measured in the bloodstreams of thousands of individuals, the one most associated with the lowest rates of disease and death was an amino acid called ergothioneine. Higher blood levels were associated with lower risk of heart disease, stroke, and death from all causes put together over a period of more than 20 years. Ergothioneine was discovered more than a century ago, but it was ignored until recently, when researchers found that humans have a highly specific transporter protein in our bodies specifically designed to pull ergothioneine out of food and into body tissue. What are the best dietary sources of ergothioneine? It isnâ€™t made by plants or animalsâ€“â€“only fungi, like mushrooms and certain soil bacteria. Plants can suck some up from the soil and animals who eat the plants can similarly benefit, but the highest levels by far have been reported in mushrooms. Mushrooms and tempehâ€”a fungi-fermented soybean cakeâ€”are the only concentrated dietary sources. As mushrooms go, shiitake and oyster mushrooms have higher levels than white button mushrooms. However, just eating a cup a day of ordinary white mushrooms can double ergothioneine concentrations in the blood. Mushroom consumption is associated with a lower risk of cancer, driven mainly by lower breast cancer rates, as well as a lower risk of dying prematurely from all causes put together. Interventional trials have found, for example, that eating just a few mushrooms a day can improve immune function. How Not to Age is out now!
